\begin_layout Title
Status consumption under wealth inequalities 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

- a case study in Tanzania
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract

\shape italic
Status consumption is known to be ubiquitous but the role played by wealth
 inequalities and exclusion in the varied contexts of developing economies
 is explored less often.
 We develop a model for status consumption by viewing the permanent ownership
 and the expenditure in excess of needs as the primary indicators of status
 in a framework of intertemporal substitution.
 Incorporating opposing effects of peer influences and extreme wealth difference
s on status competitions in the model, we use the data on durable goods
 ownership from the Tanzanian LSMS consumption microdata to discuss how
 a segregation of overall quality in an environment of price heterogeneity
 may characterise status consumption in a developing economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Empirical studies in both developed and developing economies have associated
 social segmentation in an economy with disproportionate spending on conspicuous
 items 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019,KausSA,ZahraIndia,JaikumarConspConIneq,FrieheGermany,heffetz_visibility"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 While some such disparities could be explained with the relevance of reference
 groups, the empirical studies are often confronted with the problems arising
 from the varied social contexts of status consumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With an aim to use a generic model for status consumption that can be extended
 across the developed and developing economies, we treat the role of spatial
 and economic boundaries explicitly in the model by considering the opposing
 roles of peer effects and wealth differences on status consumption.
 We note that on one hand, peer effects are meant to encourage status consumptio
n while on the other the extreme wealth differences have a necessary effect
 of making visible consumption appear futile since the consumers can hardly
 overcome glaring (and thus visible) wealth differences.
 Seeking conditions under which the demand for conspicuous goods may be
 reduced (or even absent) in spatially or economically separated reference
 groups 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The terminology of goods vs commodities provided by Cramer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CramerIncomePrice1973"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is used throughout the current chapter.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we develop a model for status consumption that interprets status in a
 context of socio-economic differences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If consumers were strictly segregated across spatial or socio-economic boundarie
s (e.g.
 class, region, race etc.), then status consumption would be necessarily
 segmented across the segregated groups.
 But status competitions are hardly limited to one's own reference group
 in our interconnected world - the consumers both compare themselves with
 the participants in their own reference groups and infer status of other
 reference groups which they don't belong to.
 Whether the extent of visible consumption associated to a particular social
 is driven by the level of segregation in an economy or not is a quantitative
 concern that must be explained with a relevant context for status and wealth
 differences.
 The poorer consumers - despite the supposed tendency to embrace the habits
 of those slightly richer than them - may not emulate the rich 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This is the idea of pecuniary emulation noted by Veblen
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 i.e.
 the notion that the habits of the rich are emulated by the poorer consumers.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 when the latter are a microscopic minority in a largely impoverished economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To explore the opposing effects of wealth differences and peer-influences
 on status consumption in quantitative terms, we fall back on the notion
 of how status consumption is used to offset existing inequalities in income
 and economic standing.
 Instead of focusing on the disproportionate demand for signaling-goods
 (i.e.
 conspicuous consumption), therefore we adopt a model based on a social-deferenc
e view of status that has been embraced in many economic studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy,corneo_snobbism,ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Here, status is seen in a wealth hierarchy that the consumer tries to offset
 (at least partly) with status-related consumption.
 More specifically, any two consumers who carry the same personal characteristic
s and have the same set of needs can compete with each other for status
 both with excess non-durable consumption (above cost of needs) and long-term
 durable goods.
 For an empirical measurement of status consumption, we use the permanent
 ownership of items (owned long-term goods) and the non-durable consumption
 in excess of needs.
 The cost of needs is inferred as the cost of owning long-term goods and
 the cost of basic needs varying across regions.
 After adjusting for her needs, a consumer is expected to optimise the utility
 she obtains from both excess and long-term possessions.
 Social or spatial characteristics matter to the consumer in this model
 through the durable goods cluster which the consumer belongs to as well
 as the price of excess and the cost of basic needs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In popular culture, status consumption often evokes images of wasteful expenditu
re and exclusive possessions that provide no economic value other than an
 attraction to people of equal affluence.
 Thus whether a consumer's newly acquired wealth - whether it be jewelry
 of acquisition of undervalued land or property - needs to be considered
 part of her necessities for higher status or wasteful conspicuous consumption
 is subjected to an endless debate.
 Since we have no way of knowing the real intentions of a consumer by evaluating
 their consumption diaries, we are left with measurements of existing  wealth
 and our own notion of necessities.
 There are two key preconditions for in the empirical analysis based on
 the model.
 The first is that there exist some basic needs in an economy – so that
 rich don’t have needs different from the poor – but only different levels
 of excess over basic needs (apart from differences in their long-term possessio
ns).
 Notice that our notion of excess excludes any maintenance costs for the
 long-term possession e.g.
 if you have a car, petrol is not an excess and also contributes to their
 status along with the assets.
 The second precondition is that the differences in bands of long-term possessio
ns would create differences in price of excess.
 With these, adding more durable goods to one's wealth or achieving more
 excess would thus both create a higher status –even if the a chances of
 perceived social mobility are low.
 With these two assumption we infer the extent of status consumption as
 the combination of excess and durable goods purchases in the economy.
 The claim we test empirically is whether the excess is affected by relative
 competition in the asset bands or the absolute regional differences due
 to spatial or economic exclusion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key advantage with the above approach is that unlike the studies in visible
 consumption, we need not rely on the assumption that conspicuous items
 are futile.
 While the futility assumption implicitly ensures the separability of demand
 for visible goods
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HopkinsKornienkoStatusGames2004,ireland_signals"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 in an empirical analysis, it neither encompasses status consumption fully
 nor does it provide a clear separation for visibility in bandwagon items
 such as electronics or cars that may both serve utility in the regular
 sense and provide status advantage.
 We thus avoid the futility assumption and interpret the more general notion
 of quality as excess that permits any high-price non-durable consumption
 or a durable good to contribute to status - a notion which we feel is necessary
 to represent the conditions of a developing economy.
 Our approach may be allow to test the significance of status consumption
 across economies without relying on proxies of cultural contexts (e.g.
 visibility surveys
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "heffetz_visibility,ZahraIndia"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 etc.).
 
\end_layout

