\begin_layout Standard
The dynamic view of status - provided by Coleman
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Corneo et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and having been widely embraced in the economic studies - presents status
 as an income-based ranking order that can be altered by the consumer with
 consumption.
 A consumer thus achieves status utility through status consumption by moving
 herself up in a ranking order that is otherwise determined by wealth and
 income.
 A model that that views consumption in the context of status as a ranking
 order based on income or wealth could be used to endogenise the role of
 social identity in conspicuous consumption as well.
 This is the view used in our intertemporal formulation of status consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To delineate the role which social characteristics and identities play in
 status consumption further, we consider how wealth differences may matter
 towards status consumption.
 Instead of assuming that the status-indicating goods in a developing country
 must be the same as those that are considered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

visible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the developed economies, we consider the role that wealth differences
 could play towards status differences in the developed economies - arguing
 that the wealth differences may be far too wide and important for the limited
 range of available visible items to matter in the status competitions in
 developing economies (where industrial development is concentrated into
 fewer urban areas).
 The relevance of wealth differences in status consumption has not been
 discussed in much detail in the literature on conspicuous consumption we
 have surveyed (except for some studies directly exploring the effect income
 inequality on conspicuous consumption with exogenously observed poverty/income
 levels or GINI indices - see Jaikumar 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JaikumarConspConIneq"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Wisman 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WismanSavingClassIdentity2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Chai et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The inclusion of long-term durable goods (e.g.
 housing) in status-related consumption has been rather arbitrary in much
 of the literature.
 Viewing status consumption in the context of wealth differences could also
