 be viewed as part of status consumption or not.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An obvious issue with viewing social identities in the same ranking order
 as that of wealth is that of scope associated with social identities.
 While some social identities may be perceived to be of higher status than
 others, the individuals that are too poor or too different from other groups
 might not compare themselves with those that are either too rich or too
 different from themselves.
 That the competitions to reach a higher status are segmented by social
 identities has been confirmed in quite a few empirical studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CharlesHurstRace,KausSA"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The role that social identities play towards consumption thus gets complicated
 as the social identities both i) limit the status consumption within themselves
 and ii) carry a status value (higher or lower) to those outside the respective
 social groups (see Timothy
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TimothyBurkeLifebuoyMen1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Srinivas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SrinivasSanskritization"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for relevance of social identities; also see Frank
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
