\begin_layout Standard
An empirical analysis with this model relies on two key measurements - the
 wealth of a consumer (which can be proxied relatively easily if the stock
 of durable goods possessed by consumer - inclusive of housing, land and
 other long-term assets - is available) and the non-durable consumption
 in excess of needs - which we hereforth refer to as excess.
 Here, the fulfillment of basic needs is not meant to offer an advantage
 to the consumer in a status competition.
 A consumer with a habit of 
\shape italic
relative 
\shape default
high-quality in consumption (or deriving higher felicity above the fulfillment
 of needs) measured as excess - in other words - would have higher status
 than another consumer who consumes less quality (excess) while the needs
 of the two consumers are the same.
 If basic needs of the two consumers being compared are the same and their
 difference in needs arise only out of their long-term possessions, then
 the addressing of needs alone does not provide any status utility than
 what is provided by the long-term possessions or characteristics.
 It follows that if there is any status related utility to be derived from
 non-durable consumption, it would be constituted in the felicity from excess
 (which is defined as distance from all needs tied to a particular reference
 group).
 It also follows that any status in a particular reference group that is
 not signaled with excess must come out of the possession of (and thus utility
 from) the long-term durable goods (or the proxy of wealth).
\end_layout

