\end_inset

 for the median costs of these durable goods).
 The details of records include the number 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{t}$
\end_inset

 of durable goods owned by the household, the reported cost 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

 at which the durable good was purchased and the price 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

 the household expects by selling the durable good in the market at the
 time of the survey.
 We refer to the price 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

 that the household expects by selling the durable good in the market as
 marked-to-market average or simply mtm average in the foregoing discussion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We find that as a recall value, the cost 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

 is particularly sensitive to measurement errors.
 Recorded by the survey at two different time-points spread across two years
 (let's call the time points 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

), these reported costs can change over the period of two years - i.e.
 the reported cost of the same durable good in 2012 (
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

) may be significantly different from the cost reported in 2014 (
\begin_inset Formula $t+1$
\end_inset

).
 This could simply be because of a different member of the same household
 providing the estimate in the two different years.
 The problem could also get worsened due to two further issues - first the
 waves are not a panel-data set in the true sense - the household visited
 in the year 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is likely to have been visited in the year 
\begin_inset Formula $t-1$
\end_inset

 but very unlikely to have been visited in the year 
\begin_inset Formula $t-2$
\end_inset

.
 Second - a significant number of households are split in multiple households
 - thus permitting more measurement errors as the new household members
 recall the cost of owned items.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to above issues with 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{t}$
\end_inset

, we use the reported price 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

 of the durable goods (i.e.
 the mtm average) as it is not recalled from consumer's memory but instead
 reflects the perceived depreciation of the durable good over time - an
 issue can be handled by averaging over 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 The total cost of the assets is achieved by multiplying th number of assets
 reported with reported price 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

.
 Around 10% of the households that were split in the periods 2010-2012 and
 in 2012-2014 have been ignored for our analyses.
\end_layout

