\begin_layout Standard
Notice that if the difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $a(p,\rho)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b(p,\rho)$
\end_inset

 is too little, then subsistence is far too difficult (and bliss far too
 easy).
 Such conditions of a narrow difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $a(p,\rho)$
\end_inset

 and low 
\begin_inset Formula $b(p,\rho)$
\end_inset

 are impossible in the real-world simply because while there is a threshold
 of discomfort which determines the subsistence, the possible level of bliss
 achievable with more money 
\begin_inset Formula $log(x)$
\end_inset

 is virtually unbounded.
 This asymmetry has implications for status consumption.
\end_layout

